For AP Seniors' Bonus Payout in 2025

Singapore Citizen residing in Singapore;

Aged 55 and above in 2025;

Assessable Income for Year of Assessment 2023 must not exceed $34,000;

Annual Value of home (as indicated on NRIC) not exceeding $31,000 as at 31 July 2024; and

Does not own more than one property.

For GSTV – Cash Payout in 2026

Singapore Citizen residing in Singapore;

Aged 21 and above in 2026;

Assessable Income for Year of Assessment 2025 must not exceed $39,000;

Annual Value (AV) of home (as indicated on NRIC) not exceeding $31,000 as at 31 December 2025; and

Does not own more than 1 property.

For GSTV – MediSave Payout in 2026

Singapore Citizen residing in Singapore;

Aged 65 and above in 2026;

Annual Value of home (as indicated on NRIC) not exceeding $31,000 as at 31 December 2025; and

Does not own more than 1 property.

Singapore Citizen;

At least 30 years old or older as of 31 December of the work year;

Earn an average gross monthly income of not more than $3,000 for the past 12 months;

Have declared your net trade income and made MediSave contributions in full if you are self-employed;

Live in a property with an annual value of $21,000 and below as at 31 December of the preceding year;

Own not more than one property; and

If you are married:

you and your spouse together not own more than one property; and

the assessable income of your spouse does not exceed $70,000 of the preceding Year of Assessment

The above is similar to the Workfare Income Supplement (WIS) criteria.

IHL students with disabilities will receive internship support services such as:

reviewing their resumes;

conducting internship search;

preparing them for interviews;

accompanying them for interviews (sitting in as observer);

advising potential employers on the student’s disabilities and support needs and;

providing job support (either virtual or in-person) during the internship.

To apply for MediFund assistance, you must:

be a Singapore Citizen;

be a subsidised patient;

have received or require treatment from a MediFund-approved institution; and

be having difficulties paying for your healthcare bills after Government subsidies and other means including MediShield Life, MediSave, and cash.

Your application will be assessed holistically, taking into consideration you and your family’s financial, health and social circumstances.

Singapore Citizen only

Born in 1995 or later, or born before 1995 and opted in to increase CPF contributions;

Net income from platform work (i.e. gross earnings minus the Fixed Expense Deduction Amount) and other employment sources does not exceed $3,000 per month;

Must have an increase in platform worker’s own share of CPF contributions to the Ordinary and Special/Retirement Account compared to the previous year

Singapore Citizen;

At least 30 years old or older as of 31 December of the work year; or at least 13 years old for persons with disabilities.

Earn an average gross monthly income of not more than $3,000 for the past 12 months;

Have declared your net trade income and made MediSave contributions in full if you are self-employed;

Live in a property with an annual value of $21,000 and below as at 31 December of the preceding year;

Own not more than one property; and

If you are married:

you and your spouse together not own more than one property; and

the assessable income of your spouse does not exceed $70,000 of the preceding Year of Assessment

 

The above is similar to the Workfare Income Supplement (WIS) criteria.

Pro Bono SG’s Community Law Centre @ Realm of Tranquility will: 

(1) Facilitate or provide legal guidance and representation to socially and virtually excluded persons; 

(2) Work closely with community partners in the North West district to provide integrated legal care to socially and virtually excluded persons in the community; 

(3) Provide training and support to community partner staff and, where relevant, their volunteers to identify potential unmet legal needs among socially and virtually excluded beneficiaries, including referring those persons for follow-up assistance at the Community Law Centre; 

(4) Provide training and support to volunteer lawyers serving at Pro Bono SG's network of community legal clinics and pro bono representation schemes; 

(5) Conduct law awareness talks for socially and virtually excluded persons/their caregivers to equip them with functional legal knowledge of their rights and protections; and 

(6) Build up a corpus of best practices and knowledge database as a centre of excellence in integrated, holistic socio-legal healing

Active Ageing Centres (AACs) provide a suite of services which include:

Active Ageing activities to keep seniors engaged within the community;

Befriending services for vulnerable seniors who require additional social support;

Making referrals for Care services when required;

Providing assistance through assuming the role of a social connector for social and lifestyle interventions to support seniors in adhering to their health plan recommendations; and

Supporting seniors in the measurement of their vital signs in adherence to their health plan.

Active Ageing Centre (Care), or AAC (Care), provides AAC services and additional care services, such as day care, community rehabilitation.

Applicants for care services may need to fulfil the services’ eligibility criteria and providers’ service boundaries, if any, and enrolments are subject to availability of vacancies.

Senior applying to stay in a nursing home must be:

Physically and/or mentally disabled because of illness;

Semi-mobile, using a wheelchair or is bedbound, and needs daily care and help with activities like going to the toilet or walking;

Unable to be cared for at home by family or paid domestic worker, and tried all other care options such as using day care, home medical, home nursing services, etc; and

Singapore Citizen (SC), Permanent Resident (PR) or foreigner
